WMI (Windows Management Instrumentation)
Q: what is WMI?

Ans: WMI is a set of extentions to the windows driver model which provides an operating
system interface through which instrumented components can provide information and
notification.
WMI is microsoft's implementation of WBEM (Web Based Enterprise Management) and CIM
(Common Information Model) from the standards from the DMTF (Distributed Management Task
Force)

Q What is the purpose of WMI

The Purpose of WMI is to define a proprietary set of environment-independent specification
which allows management information to be shared between management applications.
Uses of WMI:
i) Hardware & Software inventory: WMI helps gather information about installed hardware
components (such as CPU, memory, Disk, etc) and software application.
ii) System Configuration: You can use WMI to query & configure system settings, security
policies, permissions & other parameters.
iii) Event Monitoring: WMI enables event-based monitoring, you can receive alerts when
specific event occurs, eg: (System Startup, logon, disk space threshold, etc.)
iv) Performance Monitoring: WMI provides performance counters and metrics for monitoring
system performance (CPU usage, memory utilization, network activity, etc.)
v) Registry files System data: WMI allows access to registry keys, values, and file system
information.
vi) Custom Management application: Developers can create custom management application
using WMI to automate tasks perform diagnostics and manage resources.

Note: WMI -> it is implemented as a service process within a shared service host (svchost). The
name of WMI service is Winmgmt. Depending on the setup, WMI Service may shut down or go
into low memory profile when no management application is being called by a management
application.

